	The size of a file can be determined by looking at the
	<a class=3D"link" href=3D"https://www.nongnu.org/ext2-doc/ext2.html#i-size=
" title=3D"i_size">ext2_inode.i_size</a> field.
    </p></div><div class=3D"sect2"><div class=3D"titlepage"><div><div><h3 c=
lass=3D"title"><a id=3D"idm140660446975776"></a>Owner and Group</h3></div><=
/div></div><p>
	Under most implementations, the owner and group are 16bit values, but on
	some recent Linux and Hurd implementations the owner and group id are
	32bit.  When 16bit values are used, only the <span class=3D"quote">=E2=80=
=9C<span class=3D"quote">low</span>=E2=80=9D</span> part should
	be used as valid, while when using 32bit value, both the <span class=3D"qu=
ote">=E2=80=9C<span class=3D"quote">low</span>=E2=80=9D</span>
	and <span class=3D"quote">=E2=80=9C<span class=3D"quote">high</span>=E2=80=
=9D</span> part should be used, the high part being shifted left
	16 places then added to the low part.
    </p><p>
	The low part of owner and group are located in
	<a class=3D"link" href=3D"https://www.nongnu.org/ext2-doc/ext2.html#i-uid"=
 title=3D"i_uid">ext2_inode.i_uid</a> and
	<a class=3D"link" href=3D"https://www.nongnu.org/ext2-doc/ext2.html#i-gid"=
 title=3D"i_gid">ext2_inode.i_gid</a> respectively.
    </p><p>
	The high part of owner and group are located in
	<a class=3D"link" href=3D"https://www.nongnu.org/ext2-doc/ext2.html#h-i-ui=
d-high" title=3D"h_i_uid_high">ext2_inode.osd2.hurd.h_i_uid_high</a> and
	<a class=3D"link" href=3D"https://www.nongnu.org/ext2-doc/ext2.html#l-i-gi=
d-high" title=3D"l_i_gid_high">ext2_inode.osd2.hurd.h_i_gid_high</a>,
	respectively, for Hurd and located in
	<a class=3D"link" href=3D"https://www.nongnu.org/ext2-doc/ext2.html#l-i-ui=
d-high" title=3D"l_i_uid_high">ext2_inode.osd2.linux.l_i_uid_high</a> and
	<a class=3D"link" href=3D"https://www.nongnu.org/ext2-doc/ext2.html#l-i-gi=
d-high" title=3D"l_i_gid_high">ext2_inode.osd2.linux.l_i_gid_high</a>,
	respectively, for Linux.
    </p></div></div><div class=3D"sect1"><div class=3D"titlepage"><div><div=
><h2 class=3D"title" style=3D"clear: both"><a id=3D"contrib-extended-attrib=
utes"></a>Extended Attributes</h2></div></div></div><p>
	Extended attributes are name:value pairs associated  permanently  with
	files and directories, similar to the environment  strings  associated
	with a process.  An attribute may be defined or undefined.  If  it  is
	defined, its value  may	be empty or non-empty.
   </p><p>
	Extended attributes are extensions to the normal attributes which  are
	associated with all inodes in the  system.  They  are  often  used  to
	provide additional  functionality  to  a  filesystem  -  for  example,=20
	additional security features such as Access Control Lists  (ACLs)  may
	be implemented using extended attributes.
   </p><p>
	Extended attributes are accessed as atomic objects. Reading  retrieves
	the whole value of an attribute and stores it  in  a  buffer.  Writing
	replaces any previous value with the new value.
   </p><p>
	Extended attributes are stored on disk blocks allocated outside of
	any inode. The <a class=3D"link" href=3D"https://www.nongnu.org/ext2-doc/e=
xt2.html#i-file-acl" title=3D"i_file_acl">i_file_acl</a> field (for
	regular files) or the <a class=3D"link" href=3D"https://www.nongnu.org/ext=
2-doc/ext2.html#i-dir-acl" title=3D"i_dir_acl">i_dir_acl</a> field
	(for directories) fields contain the block number of the allocated data
	block used to store the	extended attributes.
   </p><div class=3D"note" style=3D"margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0.5in=
;"><h3 class=3D"title">Note</h3><p>
	Inodes which have all identical extended attributes may share the same
	extended attribute block.
   </p></div><p>
	The attribute values are on the  same block  as their  attribute entry
	descriptions, aligned to the end of the  attribute block.  This allows
	for additional attributes to be added more easily. The  size  of  entry
	headers  varies with  the length  of the	attribute name.
   </p><div class=3D"sect2"><div class=3D"titlepage"><div><div><h3 class=3D=
"title"><a id=3D"extended-attribute-layout"></a>Extended Attribute Block La=
yout</h3></div></div></div><p>
	The block header is followed by multiple entry descriptors. These entry
	descriptors are variable in size, and aligned to <code class=3D"constant">=
EXT2_XATTR_PAD</code>
	(4) byte boundaries. The entry descriptors are sorted by attribute name,
	so that two extended attribute blocks can be compared efficiently.
    </p><p>
	Attribute values are aligned to the end of the block, stored in
	no specific order. They are also padded to <code class=3D"constant">EXT2_X=
ATTR_PAD</code> (4)
	byte boundaries. No additional gaps are left between them.
